Welcome to the start of a new school year! We realize this has been, and continues to be, a deeply unsettling time for communities across our country. Though many things are still uncertain, please rest assured that students‚Äô education at K12-powered schools is not one of them.

In the midst of seeing unprecedented interest in our programs, our teams have been hard at work strengthening operations to better serve each student‚Äôs learning needs. Please know that any initial challenges students may face will be resolved in the coming days and weeks.

Please refer to communication from your school regarding important instructions during the high volume start to this school year, and please continue to check the K12 Help Page for updates: https://www.help.k12.com/s/article/Service-Disruption.

We are excited about the great things to come throughout this new school year, as we continue to serve our growing school community!

Destinations students have the opportunity to take exploration courses that allow them to learn more about the career pathways offered.

post_text:
Online Summer Camps through Destinations Career Academy are available!

K12‚Äôs Destinations Career Academy (DCA) will host free career exploration summer classes for students in grades 8-11, along with a free online DCA Coding Camp for students ages 13-18.

The free online DCA summer camps and classes offer a safe and engaging way for high school students to keep their minds sharp and take their first steps in exploring long-term career pathways.

DCA Summer School will offer exploratory courses in Business and Marketing, Health, and Information Technology from June 24-July 22, 2020.

DCA Coding Camp will feature two courses: Video Game Design & Programming from June 15-27, and Virtual Reality from July 6-17, 2020.

Virtual campers who complete at least one of the two Coding Camp sessions will be eligible to participate in an eSports Tournament hosted by the High School eSports League (HSEL) in late July.

The answer is A! With the "War in Europe" spreading in the early 1940s, President Roosevelt knew he might soon have a massive military that would need morale assistance. He asked six private organizations ‚Äî the YMCA, the YWCA, the National Catholic Community Service, the National Jewish Welfare Board, the Traveler's Aid Association, and the Salvation Army ‚Äî for their help.

Rather than just draw straws or split up areas on a map, the six organizations combined into a mass that focused on one demographic, the troops.
